alerts.description:
Snowfall, with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected.

Moderate to heavy snow will spread into southern Manitoba Friday night into Saturday morning. Approximately 10 to 15 centimetres is expected by the time the snow begins to ease Saturday evening, with locally higher amounts where terrain features may enhance snowfall intensity.

###

Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow.

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ec.storm.ec@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

alerts.description:
Snowfall, with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected.

Snow will intensify across southern Manitoba this morning as a trough of low pressure approaches the province. The snow will continue through most of the day before tapering off late this afternoon or tonight. Bands of snow will continue to move across southern Manitoba today as a trough of low pressure approaches the province. There have been reports of very poor visibility in the heavier snow bands.

The snow will continue through most of the day before tapering off late this afternoon or tonight. Most areas will see upwards of 10 cm accumulation, although 15 cm will fall in parts the Parklands area of western Manitoba.

A cold northwest wind will support off lake snow flurries tonight. Accumulating snow will continue along the east and southeast shores of Lake Winnipeg and Lake Manitoba through the night.

###

Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow.

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ec.storm.ec@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
